  "prompt": "Does it cost Starbucks more for the cup their coffee goes in, or the actual coffee itself?",
  "response": "The cost components for Starbucks' coffee can vary significantly based on factors such as location, type of coffee, and market conditions. Generally speaking, the cup and other packaging materials can be a significant cost factor for Starbucks. According to industry analysis and reports, in some cases, the cost of the cup and packaging can be higher than the cost of the actual coffee beans used to make the beverage. \n\nSeveral factors contribute to this, including the quality and branding of the cup, environmental considerations (such as eco-friendly materials), and supply chain logistics. Conversely, coffee beans, while influenced by commodity prices and origin of sourcing, typically account for a smaller percentage of the overall cost of a Starbucks drink compared to the packaging and operational expenses involved in the business. However, precise figures can fluctuate based on the region and specific circumstances.",
